
\lettrine[lines=4]{\color{black!45}T}{here} are three different states of the matter: solid, liquid and gas. This chapter deals with the properties of solids and liquids. On one hand, liquids exhibit peculiar properties. Liquids are not isolated as they are in contact with the atmosphere. The molecules of a liquid that are closer to the atmosphere can escape forming a vapor and this vapor exerts a certain pressure called vapor pressure. For example, this vapor pressure is what your body feels when the weather is very humid and your skin gets sticky. On the other hand, solids are made of an arrangement of molecules or atoms with a very rigid structure. Their structure is periodic and repeats all over the space. Solids also conduct heat very well as the close connection between the particles of a solid helps propagate energy. At the same time, the molecules of liquids and solids interact with each other through strong intermolecular forces. Hydrogen bonds are an important type of intermolecular force. These forces are responsible for the structure of the proteins as well as for the differences between the boiling and melting point of liquids and solids. Mind that some liquids such as water have a high boiling point whereas others such as acetone have a lower boiling point. 